WEBVTT

00:02.849 --> 00:04.131
Once about Prairie View. Prairie View. I said, I 
think I made the appointment because I wanted to

00:05.113 --> 00:10.942
talk with him. I was quite prepared to do what we 
could to help political science at Prairie View.

00:18.734 --> 00:31.253
And I told Dr. Williams at the moment, the 
Department of Political Science at Prairie View

00:18.734 --> 00:31.253
is headed by a man with a master's degree in 
education.

00:33.528 --> 00:38.716
who is scared of President Thomas. They will not, 
Thomas will not allow their students to come to us

00:41.019 --> 00:50.152
for an MPA. One of their assistants in the 
admissions office wanted to come. I'm sure Thomas

00:54.859 --> 00:56.702
said no. I had a faculty member, a woman, who'd been 
on the faculty A&M. I can't give you her name

01:03.964 --> 01:05.766
offhand. Black woman. In terms of affirmative 
action, you can't be more affirmative. And she was

01:14.276 --> 01:15.097
good. She now has a PhD and is teaching, I think, in 
Louisiana Southern, maybe. And

01:22.086 --> 01:28.013
I said, what can be done about this? And I'll never 
forget William's part. What we really ought to do

01:31.493 --> 01:36.840
is close it up. Did you see the morning paper in the 
Houston op-ed? Yes. They're a law and medical

01:39.564 --> 01:43.089
school. Because I thought, in terms of 
management, neither Texas Southern or Prairie

01:43.109 --> 01:52.762
View have a very good record. The more recent 
generals have been somewhat of an improvement.

02:00.063 --> 02:18.222
Let's see, Dr. Williams and Dr. Calhoun

02:00.063 --> 02:18.222
move out from university-level administration 
in the mid-'70s, six and seven, and Jarvis Miller

02:00.063 --> 02:18.222
and Mac Prescott take over. Did that change 
anything for you as a department head? Not a lot.

02:22.807 --> 02:27.572
Prescott was very helpful because it was under him 
the MPA went through. and he was a guiding piece and

02:28.244 --> 02:32.148
so on.

02:34.851 --> 02:45.722
Environmental design wanted in on it, several 
people wanted to cut in on it by that point and he

02:34.851 --> 02:45.722
held the line and we went with the design that it had 
been. Jarvis Miller I had no connection with

02:48.285 --> 02:56.614
except we all remember when he said everybody will 
be in their offices from eight to five.

02:59.952 --> 03:02.455
and what he thought was going on. He apparently had 
seen some people jogging at odd hours, and there

03:02.495 --> 03:10.222
was interesting reactions to that. But

03:10.523 --> 03:15.568
no, no special problem. The school was growing so 
rapidly and all the rest, we were hitting the

03:16.148 --> 03:21.774
problem of large classes. And how did you all face 
that? with large classes. But taught by? I

03:28.973 --> 03:31.837
insisted. Oh, one thing my predecessor had done 
was to do 206

03:32.057 --> 03:46.480
and 7 by lectures and assistant professors, upper 
division by associate professors, and graduate

03:32.057 --> 03:46.480
work by full professors. I said, I'm sorry, this is 
coming to a screeching halt. And everybody will at

03:50.698 --> 03:55.863
least have one section of 206 and 7. And I took an 
honors course in 206 myself as my one teaching job

03:56.544 --> 04:06.295
for the moment, my way of illustration. But all 
sections were taught by faculty. Yes. I'll say

04:13.257 --> 04:26.195
with a few exceptions, I did give some graduate 
assistants a section after they'd been here as

04:13.257 --> 04:26.195
graduate students at least one year. Can you share 
any goofy, loony, only at A&M-like events that you

04:27.757 --> 04:37.510
coped with as a department head?

04:40.190 --> 04:58.700
Well, I was told that if I hadn't been coming, that 
the departmental graduate students, of whom

04:40.190 --> 04:58.700
there were three or four on the highly liberal 
side, would have hung rubber rudder in effigy that

04:40.190 --> 04:58.700
spring, which would have been an interesting 
problem to inherit.

05:02.366 --> 05:05.151
No, I don't know anything startling. Any jokes 
that got played on any faculty member by the

05:05.502 --> 05:11.689
students or anything like that? Not that I can 
think of. We did have one faculty member harassing

05:15.253 --> 05:24.543
the lady graduate students who finally left.

05:24.603 --> 05:34.935
Did you ever have any midnight calls by anybody 
about anything supposedly happening in the

05:24.603 --> 05:34.935
department?

05:35.455 --> 05:38.419
One funny one involves Linda.

05:41.923 --> 06:02.087
I get a call that

05:41.923 --> 06:02.087
Linda would like to come talk to me, and she is the 
wife of Ralph Hambrick, who is an assistant

05:41.923 --> 06:02.087
professor, very good.

06:06.050 --> 06:13.982
We

06:06.050 --> 06:13.982
weren't sure at first. No, I'm sorry. Hamrick's

06:16.046 --> 06:21.394
wife is not named Linda. Hamrick's wife is 
calling, sir, like Mary or something. She wants to

06:25.841 --> 06:27.343
talk to him. Well, we're over across the road over 
there, and she comes to our house to talk. She said,

06:35.075 --> 06:36.737
Oh, dear, I've got problems. My husband is going 
with somebody else. And if it

06:43.785 --> 06:53.115
just weren't for Linda, I thought, oh, God, Linda 
is Gary Holder's wife. For God's sake, where are we

06:53.235 --> 06:55.297
into it? Well, it turned out Linda is also the name 
of one of our secretaries. So I kept a straight face

07:00.043 --> 07:03.006
to find out what, Linda, are we talking about?

07:09.626 --> 07:12.109
It turned out that it was the... The secretary. Our 
departmental secretary.

07:20.180 --> 07:26.347
And eventually, Ralph and his wife divorce, and he 
marries Linda. And Ralph is now at the University

07:27.008 --> 07:32.976
of Richmond, and full professor, and Linda is his 
wife. But it was a little uncertain for a bit whose

07:33.918 --> 07:39.745
wife. Did anyone ever, from outside the 
appropriate scope of the department, did anyone

07:40.266 --> 07:49.818
try to ever intervene to meddle? An A&M former 
student, a board member, a politician? Anybody

07:57.107 --> 08:00.271
try to influence an admission or a grade? No more. 
You're talking about the senator? Yeah, Bull of

08:03.773 --> 08:08.039
the Brassets.

08:09.662 --> 08:28.849
Well, I got word from the dean that

08:09.662 --> 08:28.849
one

08:09.662 --> 08:28.849
of my lectures,

08:09.662 --> 08:28.849
Dan

08:09.662 --> 08:28.849
is now with the

08:32.963 --> 08:44.738
controller's office in Florida, I think, Dan 
Burns, had made comments about political

08:32.963 --> 08:44.738
corruption in Texas. And

08:46.019 --> 09:01.198
Moore had made the cover of Time at one time in 
connection with the scandals prior to Ben Barnes

08:46.019 --> 09:01.198
and the rest of it. and that Moore was after Dan 
Burns. Well, I went to Benton, and I said, what?

09:13.121 --> 09:16.946
Well, Benton said, we've got a clipping file over 
in the library. And he got me all the clippings

09:18.047 --> 09:29.802
about Moore's insurance scandal activities, 
into which he was up to his ass in problems. and made

09:30.811 --> 09:33.594
a Xerox of them for me. And I sent that file about 
Moore to Maxwell. And I never heard another word.

09:40.362 --> 09:45.989
Now, what went on, I don't know.

09:46.449 --> 09:52.436
Did you ever get a complaint from a parent or anyone 
about us? Yes, on Elias Thermos for teaching

09:52.676 --> 09:58.303
revolution.

09:59.785 --> 10:06.551
Because on his reading list is Das Kapital and 
several other books. They're not required

10:06.791 --> 10:10.375
reading, but on the reading list. And I called 
Elias and I said, what gives? He said, well, we

10:14.739 --> 10:20.144
discussed revolution, of course, and the 
political theory. I said, OK. Don't worry, Elias.

10:23.366 --> 10:24.888
I think I can take care of this. And I

10:24.988 --> 10:29.472
said, We have a policy in political science, 
particularly in light of our situation in A&M and

10:30.802 --> 10:48.848
the military, that we have a policy that it is 
absolutely essential that you know your enemy.

10:48.868 --> 10:49.710
I never heard any more.

10:52.714 --> 10:54.216
Did anyone ever try to... Excuse me. Don't 
forget... OK, I was about to ask, did anyone ever

10:57.683 --> 11:13.908
try to, from outside the appropriate scope of the 
department, ever try to influence a grade that

10:57.683 --> 11:13.908
someone received or might receive?

11:20.619 --> 11:21.480
Not really. I never had any particular pressure. I 
handled

11:26.422 --> 11:43.805
a great appeal once, which caused me to give some 
thought to the A&M judicial system. I was acting

11:45.106 --> 11:56.361
head one Christmas vacation for Kirkpatrick. And 
a

11:57.067 --> 12:17.590
great appeal came in from

11:57.067 --> 12:17.590
a student and his parents because if it stood, he 
wasn't going to graduate.

12:19.032 --> 12:25.960
